00:56:37.690 --> 00:56:41.570
it's great to have a
dramatic entrance [laughter].

00:56:41.570 --> 00:56:42.870
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Yeah.

00:56:42.870 --> 00:56:44.170
&gt;&gt; Yeah [inaudible].

00:56:44.170 --> 00:56:45.470
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Well, had
a dramatic history, so --

00:56:45.470 --> 00:56:47.010
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: I don't
think your microphone's quite

00:56:47.010 --> 00:56:48.310
working out.

00:56:48.310 --> 00:56:49.610
But I just want to say, just

00:56:49.610 --> 00:56:52.670
in introducing Natalie while she
catches her breath and drinks,

00:56:52.670 --> 00:56:58.420
that one of the poems that I
love in this collection is sort

00:56:58.420 --> 00:57:01.730
of an essay in American
arithmetic by Natalie Diaz.

00:57:01.730 --> 00:57:05.290
And I -- like I said, I
have a critical taste.

00:57:05.290 --> 00:57:09.960
I have a taste for the critical,
the reading within poetry,

00:57:09.960 --> 00:57:11.700
the conversation, the dialog.

00:57:11.700 --> 00:57:13.470
It's really just my style.

00:57:13.470 --> 00:57:15.790
There's many, many
other styles of writing.

00:57:15.790 --> 00:57:20.300
But I so appreciate
that poem in particular.

00:57:20.300 --> 00:57:21.830
I don't know if you
want to read it or not.

00:57:21.830 --> 00:57:23.130
And --

00:57:23.130 --> 00:57:24.430
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Yeah, yeah.

00:57:24.430 --> 00:57:26.230
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: Yeah,
though would be great.

00:57:26.230 --> 00:57:29.710
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

00:57:29.710 --> 00:57:32.300
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Good
morning [foreign words].

00:57:32.300 --> 00:57:35.770
American Arithmetic.

00:57:35.770 --> 00:57:40.600
Native Americans make up less
than 1% of the population

00:57:40.600 --> 00:57:46.470
of America, .8% of 100%.

00:57:46.470 --> 00:57:49.810
Oh, mine efficient country.

00:57:49.810 --> 00:57:53.220
I do not remember the
days before America --

00:57:53.220 --> 00:57:57.690
I do not remember the days
when we were all here.

00:57:57.690 --> 00:58:02.230
Police kill Native Americans
more than any other race.

00:58:02.230 --> 00:58:04.150
Race is a funny word.

00:58:04.150 --> 00:58:09.400
Race implies someone will win,
implies I have as good a chance

00:58:09.400 --> 00:58:15.570
of winning as -- who wins
the race which isn't a race?

00:58:15.570 --> 00:58:20.860
Native Americans make up
1.9% of all police killings,

00:58:20.860 --> 00:58:28.280
higher than any race, and we
exist as .8% of all Americans.

00:58:28.280 --> 00:58:31.690
Sometimes race means run.

00:58:31.690 --> 00:58:33.910
We are not good at math.

00:58:33.910 --> 00:58:35.570
Can you blame us?

00:58:35.570 --> 00:58:39.270
We've had an American education.

00:58:39.270 --> 00:58:43.720
We are Americans and we are
less than 1% of Americans.

00:58:43.720 --> 00:58:49.700
We do a better job of dying
by police than we do existing.

00:58:49.700 --> 00:58:52.940
When we are dying,
who should we call?

00:58:52.940 --> 00:58:54.240
The police?

00:58:54.240 --> 00:58:56.050
Or our senator?

00:58:56.050 --> 00:59:00.340
Please, someone, call my mother.

00:59:00.340 --> 00:59:04.510
In Arithmetic and in America,
divisibility has rules --

00:59:04.510 --> 00:59:07.620
divide without remainder.

00:59:07.620 --> 00:59:10.820
At the National Museum
of the American Indian,

00:59:10.820 --> 00:59:15.660
68% of the collection is
from the United States.

00:59:15.660 --> 00:59:20.970
I am doing my best to not
become a museum of myself.

00:59:20.970 --> 00:59:25.060
I am doing my best to
breathe in and out.

00:59:25.060 --> 00:59:30.280
I am begging -- let me be
lonely but not invisible.

00:59:30.280 --> 00:59:33.540
But in this American
city with all its people,

00:59:33.540 --> 00:59:38.210
I am Native American, less
than one, less than whole.

00:59:38.210 --> 00:59:41.360
I am less than myself.

00:59:41.360 --> 00:59:44.320
Only a fraction of a body.

00:59:44.320 --> 00:59:50.280
Let's say, I am only a hand, and
when I slip it beneath the shirt

00:59:50.280 --> 00:59:54.970
of my lover I disappear
completely.

00:59:56.510 --> 01:00:06.270
[ Applause ]

01:00:06.270 --> 01:00:07.800
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: That's
such a wonderful poem

01:00:07.800 --> 01:00:12.780
because it shows how poems
can both contain what we seek

01:00:12.780 --> 01:00:15.910
in prose, which is the
statistical analysis,

01:00:15.910 --> 01:00:18.940
and total subvert
it and explode it

01:00:18.940 --> 01:00:22.040
with a kind of lyrical
intensity.

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:23.820
So, thank you so much
for reading that.

01:00:23.820 --> 01:00:25.250
Do you want to read another one?

01:00:25.250 --> 01:00:26.550
You up for it?

01:00:26.550 --> 01:00:28.350
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: Yes.

01:00:28.350 --> 01:00:30.980
[ Applause ]

01:00:30.980 --> 01:00:32.280
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Elise
Foerster: Please do.

01:00:32.280 --> 01:00:33.580
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Yeah.

01:00:33.580 --> 01:00:34.880
Don't forget, you don't
have to feel poor for me.

01:00:34.880 --> 01:00:36.350
This happens to people
in much worse ways.

01:00:36.350 --> 01:00:39.170
My trip here was so much easier
than people's trip trying

01:00:39.170 --> 01:00:40.550
to cross the border
right now, to --

01:00:40.550 --> 01:00:41.850
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich:
Yeah, exactly.

01:00:41.850 --> 01:00:43.150
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: --
to save their lives,

01:00:43.150 --> 01:00:44.950
so this is quite lucky.

01:00:44.950 --> 01:00:49.500
[ Applause ]

01:00:49.500 --> 01:00:50.970
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: This
one kind of goes fast,

01:00:50.970 --> 01:00:57.070
so I'm hoping I have enough
hydration in me for it.

01:00:57.070 --> 01:00:59.090
This actually began
with a line --

01:00:59.090 --> 01:01:04.190
I was reading Orlando
Wright's book, <i>Bone Right </i>.

01:01:04.190 --> 01:01:08.750
That's a book that's
made a big impact on me,

01:01:08.750 --> 01:01:11.820
and you'll hear a line in
here that says Orlando Zero.

01:01:11.820 --> 01:01:14.980
And I was thinking about that
little white skull of space

01:01:14.980 --> 01:01:20.950
that he images so
powerfully in his book.

01:01:20.950 --> 01:01:23.610
So you'll hear that
little section.

01:01:23.610 --> 01:01:25.280
Dome Riddle.

01:01:25.280 --> 01:01:28.630
Tonight I am riddled
by this sick soul,

01:01:28.630 --> 01:01:32.760
this right bowling ball zipped
in the sad sack carrying case

01:01:32.760 --> 01:01:36.440
of my face, this over-round
bone Jack-in-the-box,

01:01:36.440 --> 01:01:38.510
this Orlando's zero --

01:01:38.510 --> 01:01:47.250
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

01:01:47.250 --> 01:01:49.510
This sticky, sweet guilt type.

01:01:49.510 --> 01:01:52.310
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

01:01:52.310 --> 01:01:54.350
This small town mania
dispensary,

01:01:54.350 --> 01:01:56.220
prescribed cranium pill,

01:01:56.220 --> 01:02:00.320
this electric blue tom-tom
drum ticking like an acne bomb,

01:02:00.320 --> 01:02:02.290
hypnotized explosive device,

01:02:02.290 --> 01:02:05.210
pensive general scalp
strapped worrier,

01:02:05.210 --> 01:02:08.210
soldier with a loaded
god complex,

01:02:08.210 --> 01:02:11.190
this Hotchkiss obliterated
headdress,

01:02:11.190 --> 01:02:14.270
Gatling-lit labyrinth,
this memory grenade,

01:02:14.270 --> 01:02:18.620
and death epithet, death
epitaph, mound of momento mori,

01:02:18.620 --> 01:02:22.540
this 22-part talisman
wearing a skirt of brass,

01:02:22.540 --> 01:02:26.540
giant ball of masa, this
god patella in the long leg

01:02:26.540 --> 01:02:30.460
of my torso, zoo of
canines and Blake's tigers,

01:02:30.460 --> 01:02:34.500
this red-skinned apple,
lamp illuminated by teeth,

01:02:34.500 --> 01:02:39.140
gang of grins, spitwad of
scheme, this jawbone of an ass,

01:02:39.140 --> 01:02:43.460
smiling sliver of smite, David's
rock striking the Goliath

01:02:43.460 --> 01:02:48.610
of my body, this library of
Babel, homegrown Golgotha,

01:02:48.610 --> 01:02:50.910
nostalgia menagerie,
melon festival,

01:02:50.910 --> 01:02:52.710
this language mausoleum --

01:02:52.710 --> 01:02:58.130
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

01:02:58.130 --> 01:03:02.000
-- this hidden glacier hungry
for a taste of titanic flesh,

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:04.800
this pleasure alter,
French-kiss sweatshop,

01:03:04.800 --> 01:03:08.450
abacus of one night stands,
hippocampus whorehouse,

01:03:08.450 --> 01:03:12.710
oubliette of regret, this church
of tongue, chapel of vengeance,

01:03:12.710 --> 01:03:16.510
cathedral of thought,
bone dome of despair --

01:03:16.510 --> 01:03:19.060
[ Speaking in Foreign Language ]

01:03:19.060 --> 01:03:21.180
-- this museum of
tribal dentistry,

01:03:21.180 --> 01:03:24.080
commodity cranium cupboard,
petrified dreamcatcher,

01:03:24.080 --> 01:03:27.130
this sun-ruined basketball
I haul,

01:03:27.130 --> 01:03:30.920
rabid gray along the seams,
perpetual missed shot,

01:03:30.920 --> 01:03:34.770
this insomnia podium, little
bowl in a big fish, brain,

01:03:34.770 --> 01:03:36.600
amphitheater, girl in the moon,

01:03:36.600 --> 01:03:39.870
this 3 a.m. war bell
doing day vision prison,

01:03:39.870 --> 01:03:43.240
this single scoop vanilla
headrush, thunderhead, fastball,

01:03:43.240 --> 01:03:48.150
lightening rod, this mad
scientist in a white lab helmet,

01:03:48.150 --> 01:03:52.040
ghost of smoking mirror, this
coyote beacon, calcium corral

01:03:52.040 --> 01:03:56.110
of pale palomino ponies, this
desert seed I am root to,

01:03:56.110 --> 01:03:58.950
night-blooming [inaudible]
rattle,

01:03:58.950 --> 01:04:02.910
this Halloween crown hat-rack
worry contraption, rainbows,

01:04:02.910 --> 01:04:05.320
drunken boat, blazing
chandelier,

01:04:05.320 --> 01:04:09.240
casa [foreign words],
this coliseum [inaudible],

01:04:09.240 --> 01:04:11.990
bore his other tiger
licking the empty shell

01:04:11.990 --> 01:04:13.980
of locus white Tortuga,

01:04:13.980 --> 01:04:17.800
this underdressed god head
forever hatching egg, this mug,

01:04:17.800 --> 01:04:20.670
again and again at my lips.

01:04:20.670 --> 01:04:24.370
And all this because tonight
I imagined you sleeping

01:04:24.370 --> 01:04:29.570
with her the way we once slept,
as intimate as a jaw, maxilla

01:04:29.570 --> 01:04:35.540
and mandible hot in the skin, in
love, our heads almost touching.

01:04:35.540 --> 01:04:37.510
&gt;&gt; Beautiful.

01:04:37.510 --> 01:04:45.230
[ Applause ]

01:04:45.230 --> 01:04:50.210
&gt;&gt; Could I just say
that my collaborator

01:04:50.210 --> 01:04:52.460
in reading that was incredible.

01:04:52.460 --> 01:04:54.260
That's like --

01:04:54.260 --> 01:05:01.040
[ Applause ]

01:05:01.040 --> 01:05:02.340
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: Like I
[inaudible] get such a gift

01:05:02.340 --> 01:05:04.130
that we get to see poetry
as physical as it is.

01:05:04.130 --> 01:05:05.950
Sometimes we forget
it's physical,

01:05:05.950 --> 01:05:07.610
we forget it's about the body.

01:05:07.610 --> 01:05:11.550
We get stuck on this like eye to
ear thing that we do with text,

01:05:11.550 --> 01:05:16.300
but that was like sometimes --
this to me is like the highlight

01:05:16.300 --> 01:05:19.840
of anything I could have read,
was watching language in motion.

01:05:19.840 --> 01:05:21.640
So, gracias.

01:05:21.640 --> 01:05:27.080
[ Applause ]

01:05:27.080 --> 01:05:28.800
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: And so I'd
love to give you a chance

01:05:28.800 --> 01:05:31.930
to ask any questions
you'd like to ask.

01:05:31.930 --> 01:05:33.620
There are mics on either side.

01:05:33.620 --> 01:05:35.370
Please come up.

01:05:35.370 --> 01:05:36.670
We have about 10 minutes.

01:05:36.670 --> 01:05:39.530
Of course I could talk
all day with these three,

01:05:39.530 --> 01:05:43.280
but I'm sure you have
questions to ask.

01:05:43.280 --> 01:05:45.300
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: And
we have a sign-in --

01:05:45.300 --> 01:05:46.600
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: We
have a sign-in, yes.

01:05:46.600 --> 01:05:47.900
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich:
Yeah, it's 12:30 I think.

01:05:47.900 --> 01:05:49.200
Is that right?

01:05:49.200 --> 01:05:51.880
1:00? 1:30.

01:05:51.880 --> 01:05:53.330
So if you want to --

01:05:53.330 --> 01:05:54.630
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: So
the mics are --

01:05:54.630 --> 01:05:56.970
yeah, the mics are
over on either side.

01:05:56.970 --> 01:05:59.190
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz: [Inaudible]
is at 12:30 [laughter].

01:05:59.190 --> 01:06:00.750
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich:
Great at that.

01:06:00.750 --> 01:06:02.420
&gt;&gt; Rob Casper: So, go ahead.

01:06:02.420 --> 01:06:06.100
&gt;&gt; My question is for the
editor of the anthology.

01:06:06.100 --> 01:06:09.440
Did you have difficulties in --

01:06:09.440 --> 01:06:13.370
did you have difficulties
in selecting the poets?

01:06:13.370 --> 01:06:16.700
What was your criteria for --

01:06:16.700 --> 01:06:20.190
how did you decide that these
words are going to be in

01:06:20.190 --> 01:06:25.020
and did you have a sort
of timeline or are you --

01:06:25.020 --> 01:06:26.320
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: Yeah.

01:06:26.320 --> 01:06:27.620
&gt;&gt; -- looking at the
criteria of their work?

01:06:27.620 --> 01:06:29.070
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich: Well,
first they had to be poets

01:06:29.070 --> 01:06:31.790
who engaged me in general,
beyond the list that,

01:06:31.790 --> 01:06:33.780
and that I felt that
had an audience.

01:06:33.780 --> 01:06:35.760
That was important to me,
too, that there were folks

01:06:35.760 --> 01:06:38.280
who were reading these poets
and were interested in them.

01:06:38.280 --> 01:06:40.210
It wasn't about the
age of the poets.

01:06:40.210 --> 01:06:42.010
It was about when they
published their first book

01:06:42.010 --> 01:06:47.460
from the year 2000
forward, and, in general,

01:06:47.460 --> 01:06:49.940
I make decisions very quickly.

01:06:49.940 --> 01:06:55.090
I knew what I wanted
and I just chose --

01:06:55.090 --> 01:06:58.920
and luckily I was allowed to
just choose out of my own taste

01:06:58.920 --> 01:07:00.640
and my own sense of
how the whole was going

01:07:00.640 --> 01:07:02.940
to come together.

01:07:06.060 --> 01:07:08.560
I did require that people
have some specific connection

01:07:08.560 --> 01:07:09.930
to a Native Nation however.

01:07:09.930 --> 01:07:12.170
That was one of my -- I'm
not about blood [inaudible]

01:07:12.170 --> 01:07:15.660
or descendancy or race
or anything about that.

01:07:15.660 --> 01:07:17.880
And I also wanted people
from different directions

01:07:17.880 --> 01:07:21.010
of geography in the country
so that I got a sense

01:07:21.010 --> 01:07:22.460
of the land, you know.

01:07:22.460 --> 01:07:25.850
Physically people who live and
have relatives on the borders

01:07:25.850 --> 01:07:31.870
of the U.S. as well as folks
from all over, and Guam

01:07:31.870 --> 01:07:34.490
and Hawaii and Alaska,
to make sure

01:07:34.490 --> 01:07:39.230
that we understand ourselves
as part of Native Nations

01:07:39.230 --> 01:07:41.510
that are connected under
this political entity

01:07:41.510 --> 01:07:44.290
of the U.S. It's really
important to me because I think

01:07:44.290 --> 01:07:48.890
that more and more we will face
challenges to our Nationhood,

01:07:48.890 --> 01:07:54.780
and I want us to have bodies of
expression that can meet that

01:07:54.780 --> 01:07:58.980
and to teach the American
public that we persist

01:07:58.980 --> 01:08:02.640
as Nations regardless of who's
going to come for our resources

01:08:02.640 --> 01:08:04.940
or our physical bodies.

01:08:06.510 --> 01:08:10.340
[ Applause ]

01:08:10.340 --> 01:08:15.630
&gt;&gt; Hi. There's a lot
of talk these days

01:08:15.630 --> 01:08:20.010
about cultural appropriation,
but I'm sure

01:08:20.010 --> 01:08:21.920
that you also want many people

01:08:21.920 --> 01:08:25.670
to read this anthology
far beyond, you know,

01:08:25.670 --> 01:08:28.350
from all cultures,
nationalities,

01:08:28.350 --> 01:08:30.420
and that you want those
people, if they're writers,

01:08:30.420 --> 01:08:34.630
to be influenced by the
writers in the book.

01:08:34.630 --> 01:08:36.610
So I was wondering if you
could talk a little bit

01:08:36.610 --> 01:08:43.050
about being influenced by
writers of other nationalities

01:08:43.050 --> 01:08:45.540
or other cultures
besides your own,

01:08:45.540 --> 01:08:50.900
and cultural appropriation
on the other hand.

01:08:50.900 --> 01:08:53.100
&gt;&gt; Jennifer Elise Foerster:
I got just my first thought,

01:08:53.100 --> 01:08:56.270
I'll just speak to that,
is that when I'm influenced

01:08:56.270 --> 01:09:00.840
by other writers,
influenced poetically,

01:09:00.840 --> 01:09:05.030
then it's because I'm
engaged with their poetics.

01:09:05.030 --> 01:09:08.680
And that may or may not -- of
course, one's poetics is always

01:09:08.680 --> 01:09:10.570
about who they are,

01:09:10.570 --> 01:09:15.140
which includes culture
and all of that.

01:09:15.140 --> 01:09:20.970
But I think the richness
of poetry in the world is

01:09:20.970 --> 01:09:25.610
that we can be influenced by
one another in our poetics

01:09:25.610 --> 01:09:29.710
and that love of each other's
poetics, whether it's --

01:09:29.710 --> 01:09:31.940
we're resonant with it
or we have differences

01:09:31.940 --> 01:09:36.430
with it is another way that we
can be a conversation and be

01:09:36.430 --> 01:09:39.440
in conversation as humans
with our differences.

01:09:39.440 --> 01:09:42.730
And so I don't think that
it has to do necessarily --

01:09:42.730 --> 01:09:47.310
it doesn't have to do with
appropriation to be, to listen,

01:09:47.310 --> 01:09:50.120
and listening is part
of that influence.

01:09:50.120 --> 01:09:51.420
&gt;&gt; Heid E. Erdrich:
One of the things

01:09:51.420 --> 01:09:54.850
that I did a little differently
with the anthology was to have

01:09:54.850 --> 01:09:58.390
in the biography people
answer certain questions

01:09:58.390 --> 01:10:01.780
in the author bio, so they talk
about who their influences are

01:10:01.780 --> 01:10:03.970
in those bios or they talk
about who mentored them

01:10:03.970 --> 01:10:05.770
so you can see the connections.

01:10:05.770 --> 01:10:09.150
Mostly Native writers
mentoring one another,

01:10:09.150 --> 01:10:11.840
even some of the people in the
book mentoring one another.

01:10:11.840 --> 01:10:16.470
But also, you know, the poets
that are meaningful to them,

01:10:16.470 --> 01:10:21.720
so you see that sort of
generational influence I think.

01:10:21.720 --> 01:10:23.150
&gt;&gt; Natalie Diaz:
And appropriation --

01:10:23.150 --> 01:10:26.220
we always forget this, like
appropriation has a lot to do

01:10:26.220 --> 01:10:29.400
with the fact that
you're erasing the people

01:10:29.400 --> 01:10:31.300
who you have taken from.

01:10:31.300 --> 01:10:33.410
You know, like America
loves to wear a headdress

01:10:33.410 --> 01:10:35.060
and they would much rather --

01:10:35.060 --> 01:10:37.420
I mean, they do nothing
to take care of Natives

01:10:37.420 --> 01:10:38.720
or to give them a place to --

01:10:38.720 --> 01:10:40.080
you know, we couldn't
even practice our religion

01:10:40.080 --> 01:10:42.480
until 1978, yeah, you know,

01:10:42.480 --> 01:10:44.980
like some of us weren't
even born then.

01:10:44.980 --> 01:10:47.210
And so I think that's
something, too, is like --

01:10:47.210 --> 01:10:50.650
and always to ask
yourself why, like why,

01:10:50.650 --> 01:10:52.510
why is this necessary to write?

01:10:52.510 --> 01:10:56.060
Like I think in the book
you can see the necessity,

01:10:56.060 --> 01:10:59.880
like these things had to be
written for these writers.

01:10:59.880 --> 01:11:01.650
And so I think that's
something to consider, too,

01:11:01.650 --> 01:11:05.550
with influences like when you
find something that, you know --

01:11:05.550 --> 01:11:08.050
it has -- so we always use
that word like, I like this.

01:11:08.050 --> 01:11:09.850
But, really, it's because
it showed you something

01:11:09.850 --> 01:11:12.360
of your life or it showed you
something of your own world.

01:11:12.360 --> 01:11:13.660
And you don't have to be Native

01:11:13.660 --> 01:11:16.970
to see our world we're
all living in in this book

01:11:16.970 --> 01:11:20.450
or the pains that we sometimes
suffer, you know, even if it's

01:11:20.450 --> 01:11:22.780
across culture or across Nation.

01:11:22.780 --> 01:11:25.570
And so I think that's
something important, too,

01:11:25.570 --> 01:11:29.450
is that appropriation is
not just the influence

01:11:29.450 --> 01:11:30.860
or engaging in a conversation.

01:11:30.860 --> 01:11:35.850
But it's also like the
obliteration or erasure

01:11:35.850 --> 01:11:39.300
of the person who that came
from, whose work that came from.

01:11:39.300 --> 01:11:43.700
So I think that's an important
thing to jump into the equation.

